’s Mother Dao (1995), and the collaborative films of Nia Dinata, challenge the naturalized methods of seeing that justify exploitation, dehumanization, and early death of people of color. By theorizing the mechanisms of visual biopolitics, Rony elucidates both its violence and its vulnerability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBiopoliticszIndonesia. 0aDocumentary filmsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aEthnographic filmsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszIndonesia. 0aWomen in mass media. 0aWomen in popular culturezIndonesia. 0aWomenzIndonesiaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478021902zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021902423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021902/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles